Fundraising

August 2024 Crypto Fundraising Report

Chris Davis

Sep 10, 2024 ⋅  16 min read

Key Insights

  • Fundraising volume dropped 4.1% MoM to $1.39 billion, cooling slightly after a 72.9% surge from June to July. Deal count also declined by 4.2% to 181, continuing its multi-month downtrend.
  • In contrast, early-stage deal volume rose 17.3% MoM, with pre-seed to Series A deals totaling $512 million. Notable deals included MetaDAO’s $2.2 million private token sale, time.fun’s $3 million seed round, and zk.Me’s $4 million seed round.
  • Core Scientific’s $400 million convertible senior note offering adds to a trend of miners raising funds to stay competitive amid rising energy costs and compressed margins.
  • The financial sector raised $318 million, with major rounds from Morpho, Ledn, and Arch accounting for 53% of the sector's total fundraising volume.

Note: In an effort to more accurately reflect sector fundraising, we have chosen to exclude mining rounds from the broader infrastructure sector and address trends within the mining sector separately.

In August 2024, deal volume declined by 4.1% MoM to $1.39 billion, following a sharp 72.9% MoM surge from June to July. Deal count dropped by 4.2% MoM to 181, continuing the multi-month downtrend that began in April 2024. The financial sector dominated fundraising volume, raising a cumulative $318 million. The infrastructure sector came in second, raising $175 million, while the networks sector trailed close behind, raising a total of $155 million.

Mining Sector Trends

In July, we saw mining companies IREN, Alps Blockchain, and Argo Blockchain raise a cumulative $534 million in post-IPO rounds. Core Scientific’s $400 million convertible senior notes offering in August adds to this growing trend of mining companies raising capital to remain operational amid rising energy costs and shrinking margins following lower block rewards post-halving. In addition to capital raises, cash-rich miners like Riot Platform have recently expanded their market share by allocating resources toward acquisitions. As mining companies navigate an increasingly competitive landscape, many are also capitalizing on alternative revenue streams such as AI, cloud computing, and energy sales.

Early Stage Deals

Early-stage deal volume grew 17.3% MoM, with a cumulative pre-seed to Series A volume of $512 million. Notable deals covered a wide range of categories, including DeSoc, Crowdfunding, Identity, and Governance.

MetaDAO

MetaDAO raised $2.2 million in a private token sale led by Paradigm with participation from various angel investors such as Meltem Demirors and Anatoly Yakovenko. MetaDAO is a Solana-native prediction market platform based on the concept of “futarchy”. The overarching thesis that underpins their product is that traditional governance systems are flawed and introducing prediction markets into governance processes leads to more optimal outcomes. The three primary failures of DAO governance that MetaDAO cites are low participation, uninformed voters, and whale and insider influence.

Through their platform DAOs can launch speculative markets around proposals, enabling market participants to bet on how a proposal's outcome will impact the token price. The market’s final decision on whether the proposal would be beneficial or detrimental to price determines whether the proposal passes or fails.

Bull Case:

MetaDAO’s product is entering the market at an opportune moment. Recent governance failures, like the attack on Compound DAO, have exposed the inefficiencies of traditional DAO voting models. Meanwhile, the mainstream success of Polymarket highlights the effectiveness of blockchain-based prediction markets in aggregating intelligence and producing rational insights. Furthermore, MetaDAO’s governance model has already proven its resilience by withstanding multiple market manipulation attempts, reinforcing its credibility. As a first mover, MetaDAO is well-positioned to quickly capture the lion’s share of trading volume, setting off a virtuous cycle where increased volume and liquidity attract more DAOs, which in turn drives further volume and liquidity.

Bear Case:

Onboarding DAOs with voting power concentrated among a few participants poses a significant challenge. Leading members may perceive the system as a threat to their self-interests and be resistant to adopting it. Additionally, although MetaDAO has successfully fended off several market manipulation attempts, its model is still relatively new, and DAOs may view the potential risks of market failure as outweighing the benefits. Since the technology behind MetaDAO isn’t novel enough to create a defensible moat, some DAOs may choose to mitigate these risks by developing their own in-house systems rather than relying on third-party solutions.

For a deeper dive into MetaDAO - check out Messari’s report, A New $META for DAOs.

time.fun

Time.fun raised a $3 million seed round led by Brevan Howard, with participation from Coinbase Ventures and various angel investors, such as Santiago R. Santos and Arthur Hayes. Time.fun is a SocialFi platform built on Base that enables creators to tokenize their time. Creator tokens can be permissionless traded or redeemed for one-on-one conversations with the creator via direct messaging, calls, or video chats. Creators benefit financially from the platform through a fee share when their time is traded or redeemed.

Bull Case:

Web2 companies like intro.co have proven that the concept of purchasing high-value time has product market fit. The key innovation that time.fun introduces is the creation of liquid markets for trading time. As a later mover, time.fun benefits from learning from the mistakes of earlier SocialFi companies like friend.tech. The SocialFi space is still relatively nascent, and if time.fun can successfully attract and retain users by improving on past SocialFi models, it has the potential to become a leading platform for creator monetization.

Bear Case:

The long-term success of time.fun will hinge on its ability to expand its core product with features that drive sustained user engagement. Friend.tech's meteoric rise, followed by near zero retention, highlights that creator markets alone aren’t sticky enough to keep users engaged over extended periods of time. Time.fun faces competition from both Web3 SocialFi platforms like Fantasy.Top and Web2 platforms like intro.co, and will need to innovate quickly to retain attention. Additionally, time.fun faces challenges in generating sustained revenue. While purchasing creator time can be a high-value offering, it’s a relatively low-frequency event. Given that time.fun's revenue is tied to trading fees, the platform will need to either find a way to drive more speculative trading volume or introduce alternative revenue streams.

Financial Sector

The financial sector captured the lion's share of fundraising volume, reaching $318 million, a 41.5% MoM increase. Deal count saw a more modest rise of 5%, increasing from 57 to 60 deals. Lending played a significant role in this growth, with major rounds from Morpho, Ledn, and Arch contributing a combined $170 million.

Morpho

Morpho raised $50 million in a private token sale led by Ribbit Capital with participation from Coinbase Ventures, Andreessen Horowitz and Pantera Capital. Morpho is a modular lending platform built on Ethereum. In Q4 2023, Morpho announced Morpho Blue, a base layer protocol that enables the permissionless creation of isolated lending markets. Unlike traditional lending protocols like Aave and Compound, Morpho eliminates the need for governance decision-making in asset listing, allowing users to permissionlessly create isolated markets with a single loan asset, a single collateral asset, and customizable lending and borrowing parameters.

Bull Case:

With interest rate cuts on the horizon, onchain yields could surpass those of T-bills, potentially driving a substantial increase in total value locked (TVL) for lending protocols. If rate cuts also foster a more risk-on environment, Morpho stands to benefit from the permissionless creation of pools for long-tail assets. As the crypto ecosystem expands and new protocols launch tokens, Morpho can offer lending and borrowing opportunities for these emerging assets—areas where industry leaders like Aave and Compound might be unwilling to go. Additionally, Morpho's ability to facilitate curated vault creation gives lenders greater flexibility and more options across a wider range of risk profiles.

Bear Case:

Lending is a highly competitive sector, with Aave currently holding a significant lead, capturing 7.8x the TVL of Morpho. Should there be increased interest from TradFi investors seeking DeFi yields, Aave is likely to be the preferred choice, as it has been battle-tested through multiple market cycles, offering users reduced smart contract risk. To capture market share from leading lending protocols like Aave, Morpho will need to continue enhancing its business development efforts to onboard high-value vault creators and attract more users to its platform.

For more insights into onchain lending - check out Messari’s report A Lending Renaissance.

Skyfire

Skyfire raised $8.5 million in a seed round with participation from Circle, Ripple, and Gemini.

The full capabilities of AI agents are hindered by their current inability to make financial transactions on behalf of users. Moreover, many agent payment use cases require microtransactions, which are impractical when using traditional Web2 payment systems. By enabling connections to a network of external APIs, Skyfire aims to become the financial stack for AI agents, providing the first major pathway for agents to autonomously make onchain payments powered by stablecoins.

Bull Case:

As a platform reliant on integrations to facilitate transactions, Skyfire's success hinges on its ability to gain adoption from Web2 enterprises. PayPal’s launch of pyUSD and Visa’s stablecoin pilot programs indicate that stablecoins have already found strong product-market fit in the Web2 financial sector. The adoption of stablecoins by these leading financial companies sends a signal to other businesses that stablecoins are a credible and acceptable technology to integrate.

Additionally, Circle’s backing of Skyfire lends further credibility to the platform, helping quell potential concerns from companies hesitant to adopt nascent technology. Should AI agents become a key method of transacting in the digital economy, Skyfire is well-positioned to build a moat through high-value integrations with Web2 enterprises.

Bear Case:

Skyfire envisions a future where traditional SaaS business models are replaced by micropayment-driven models that grant access to specific, intent-based information. However, companies may find that they generate more revenue through the SaaS model than by opening their APIs to micropayments. Moreover, widespread consumer adoption of AI agents will require significant trust in their ability to accurately fulfill requests. It’s possible that Skyfire could be directionally correct in its thesis, but too early for adequate adoption by everyday consumers.

Infrastructure Sector

Fundraising volume in the infrastructure sector declined by 19.5% to $175 million, with the number of deals dropping by 28.5%, from 28 to 20. As mentioned earlier, rounds in the mining sector have been excluded to provide a clearer view of changes within the broader infrastructure sector.

Sahara AI

Sahara AI raised $43 million in a strategic round led by Binance Labs, Polychain Capital, and Pantera Capital.

Sahara AI is a decentralized AI blockchain platform designed to challenge centralized AI networks by providing a privacy-focused, human-centered alternative that rewards users for their contributions to the network. The platform includes an AI-native blockchain, a marketplace for crowdsourcing AI assets, development tools for both technical and non-technical creators, and encrypted vaults for secure data storage.

Though Sahara AI is still in its early stages, the project has already attracted considerable attention within the crypto community, with over 300,000 users signing up to participate in its first initiative, the Prometheus Program.

Bull Case:

Sahara's vision is one of the most ambitious among early-stage projects in the decentralized AI sector. However, Sahara is off to a strong start, gaining initial adoption from notable names in the tech industry. Their initial go-to-market attracted enterprise clients like MIT, Microsoft, USC, and Motherson Group, who leveraged their natively built-in decentralized data marketplace to enhance AI model training.

A core feature of Sahara’s platform is the incentivization of human contributions in the form of data, models, or services such as labeling and data collection. As AI-generated content increasingly populates the internet, these human inputs could become a highly valuable resource for mitigating "model collapse.” If Sahara can prove itself to major AI companies, it stands to carve out a valuable niche in enterprise AI training.

Bear Case:

Disrupting centralized AI is a common talking point for projects at the intersection of crypto and AI. However, many decentralized AI companies have struggled to keep pace with their centralized counterparts, who benefit from massive economies of scale. In this context, there is a risk that Sahara may overextend itself by trying to innovate across multiple layers of the AI stack. As the project moves beyond its initial development phases, it will need to demonstrate its capacity to execute on its ambitious roadmap.

For more insights into the decentralized AI landscape, check out Messari’s Dissecting the Intersection of AI and Crypto.

Andrena

Andrena raised $18 million in an extended Series A round led by Dragonfly with participation from numerous firms such as CMT Digital, Robot Ventures, and ParaFi Capital. Andrena is the parent company of DAWN, a decentralized physical infrastructure network (DePIN) protocol built on Solana that seeks to decentralize broadband internet.

DAWN’s vision is to “transform the Internet from a provider-owned model to a consumer-owned model.” By combining blockchain technology with advancements in fixed-wireless broadband, DAWN leverages a decentralized network of at-home providers to deliver high-performance internet at the lowest market cost. By bypassing the prohibitively high CapEx associated with traditional internet infrastructure, DAWN has a unique opportunity to compete with major centralized Internet Service Providers (“ISPs”) like AT&T and Verizon.

Bull Case:

DAWN benefits significantly from the industry connections and hardware infrastructure established by its parent company, Andrena. These inherited advantages provide DAWN with a head start compared to other DePIN networks, which need to build infrastructure and forge business relationships from the ground up. This head start has enabled DAWN to quickly go to market, testing its protocol with 3,000 subscribers in the New York City area. These initial trials have generated approximately $1 million in annual recurring revenue, showcasing the protocol's ability to drive revenue in the early stages of the network. If DAWN can replicate this success as it scales, it is well-positioned to become a leading player in the DePIN sector.

Bear Case:

DAWN’s business model relies on scaling network effects through a flywheel powered by token incentives. While token incentives are effective for scaling the supply side of the network, the greater challenge lies in driving sustained demand. Furthermore, the scalability of the fixed-wireless technology underpinning DAWN’s growth may be overstated. If DAWN cannot provide an end-user experience that competes with incumbent ISPs in terms of quality and reliability, it may face difficulties in attracting consumers who are accustomed to high-quality service from established providers.

For a deeper dive into DAWN - check out Messari’s report, The DAWN of DePIN: Commoditizing Internet Bandwidth with Fixed-Wireless Broadband.

Networks Sector

The networks sector experienced a 36.4% MoM increase in volume, reaching a total of $155 million, despite an 8.7% decline in deal count, dropping from 23 to 21 deals. This significant divergence between volume and deal count is largely driven by Story Protocol’s substantial $80 million Series B round.

Story Protocol

Story Protocol raised $80 million in a Series B round led by Andreessen Horowitz with co-investment from Polychain Capital. Story Protocol is an EVM-equivalent L1 designed to make intellectual property (“IP”) fully programmable by rearchitecting the infrastructure that underpins the IP industry.

For many creators, the high costs and complexities of IP licensing and arbitration lead to lost monetization opportunities. Story’s architecture removes these barriers by enabling permissionless licensing backed by human-readable legal agreements, automatic royalty distribution, and programmable arbitration. By solving for these inefficiencies, Story enables creators to take full economic advantage of their IP, unlocking latent value within the creator economy.

Bull Case:

Attracting high-quality builders is essential for the adoption of any network. Story employs a dual-pronged strategy for developer acquisition, running both external hackathons and a high-touch internal developer program called Story Academy. So far, Story has proven to be an attractive platform for builders, with 10% of ETHDenver hackathon projects choosing to build on Story, and 20% of the General Hackathon winners coming out of this cohort.

Beyond engaging native developers, Story’s integrations into third-party Web2 and Web3 applications point to product-market fit across a variety of sectors, such as DeSoc, AI, and collaborative art. If Story can continue to build on this early momentum, it has the potential to begin forming a moat through valuable third-party integrations and a hand-tailored developer community.

Bear Case:

Not all IP holds equal value, and without an attractive supply of high-quality IP, there will be little demand for licensing. As a developer-led platform without a flagship product, Story’s success hinges on developers transforming the protocol’s value propositions into products that attract top-tier creators. Moreover, capturing significant value from the mainstream creator economy will eventually require integrations with Web2 creator platforms like Spotify and YouTube. However, forming these partnerships is a significant challenge, as large Web2 enterprises are often slow to adopt nascent technologies like crypto.

To learn more about Story Protocol, check out Messari’s report The Story So Far: An Intelligent Approach to Intellectual Property.

Essential

Essential raised $11 million in a round led by Archetype. Essential is the first declarative blockchain, shifting from traditional transaction-based systems to an intent-driven model. In contrast to the imperative approach, which focuses on executing specific instructions, Essential enables state updates based on outcomes without the need for execution.

Essential uses a constraint-based language called Pint for programmable intents, enabling developers to directly manage state updates and build declarative applications. With the recent launch of its pre-alpha devnet, Essential invites developers to experiment with and test the network.

Bull Case:

As intent-based models gain adoption in the DeFi ecosystem, Essential is well-positioned to capitalize on the growing familiarity with this approach. In Essential’s early growth stages, users with a basic understanding of intents may be intrigued enough by the intent-centric architecture to spend time exploring the ecosystem. While onboarding users and developers into a new platform often requires heavy business development and incentives, if Essential is able to deliver an order of magnitude better user experience through its declarative architecture, it could fast-track organic adoption. Similar to how Solana's superior experience attracted users from Ethereum, Essential may be able to acquire users by offering a fundamentally better solution that creates stronger network effects naturally.

Bear Case:

While Essential’s declarative model presents potential advantages, these benefits may not be compelling enough to incentivize developers to learn a new language and invest time in an unproven ecosystem. Moreover, if the intent structures being developed on traditional imperative blockchains deliver a comparable end-user experience, Essential’s value proposition may not be strong enough to drive user migration. Without clear, “only possible on Essential” use cases, the platform risks falling into a “build it, and they will come” scenario, where adoption fails to materialize despite the technical innovation.

Conclusion

In August 2024, fundraising saw a slight decline, with volume dropping 4.1% MoM to $1.39 billion and deal count falling 4.2%, continuing a multi-month downtrend. However, early-stage deal volume rose 17.3% MoM to $512 million. The sharp increase in deal count seen in the spring has now leveled off, returning to levels similar to Q4 2023. Seasonality may play a role in this decline, as summer typically slows financial activity across the industry. With potential rate cuts and the U.S. presidential election approaching, the final months of 2024 could offer clearer signals to gauge the broader market trend.
